 than what I thought originally. Tonight, what came as a total shock was to find that Thorkin (who I had actually considered giving guild leadership to at one point) and Emberglow, the two people who had been in Pax just as long as I had, and two officers  at that, had quit.<br>
<br>
To me, that kind of sounded the death knell of Pax Familla. Well, even though this is only a video game, I almost cried over that. I mean, I was almost totally blown away. Pax groups were forming alot and having fun together. I hadn't heard any recent comments in weeks but about how good Pax was doing and how people enjoyed being in it. And then people just stopped logging on, people stopped chatting despite my efforts to keep them talking and being friends with each other.<br>
<br>
Well, per the suggestion of a few remaining members, I have posted this poll for you. A majority of complaints that everyone heard before, and what is the complaint of what someone told me tonight, is that Pax cannot help them achieve high end goals of the game. Therefore, it was suggested to change the guild to a 46th+ minimum requirement and attempt to be a high end guild so we can attract high end members and keep existing high end members. Current Paxers would be grandfathered in of course, and I would make attempts to keep the rule of allowing your twinks in, no matter what level. Doing this would probably mean that we would have more raids on dungeons, and of course, planes.<br>
<br>
The other option, that has been offered to me before, and might still be in effect, is to merge with Swords of Sacrifice. Before we did the merger with Sons of Tao, this option was set before me by Sleepingbear, the leader of Swords of Sacrifice. Wanting to keep the Pax identity, I turned him down, but formed an alliance with them so we could go on their raids and hopefully keep members through the prospect of raids. Well needless to say, I found out that not many Paxers took advantage of the raids offered by Swords of Sacrifice. Go figure. I have asked one of his officers, a personal friend of mine, to see if that offer is still open. For the sake of time, I have posted that option here anyway as I'm pretty sure it is.<br>
<br>
Myself, I cannot decide what I would want to do. So, until I give this further personal thought, I will not vote.<br>
<br>
Yours, humbly, Suntoucher. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#339999><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub29.ezboard.com/utimont2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Timont2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#000099>(3/7/02 12:24:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub29.ezboard.com/fpaxfamillafrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=761.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Future of Pax Familla</span><hr size=1> I have some knowledge of Guild mergers from watching friends play EQ long before I started playing.  For example one guild merged with Institute.  The guild that merged lost the guild name and tag.  Institute was more of a high level guild at the time before Kunark.  As EQ grew and so did other characters levels Institute was still a high level guild but had lost people that headed to level 60.  Institute relized what they wanted to acheive as far as leveling and getting equipment.  However they did not want to lose the guild tag.  Institute merged with Crimson Eternity but left all twinks in Institute.  Institute still lives and has some higher level characters in as of date.<br>
<br>
A guild can merge and still live on.<br>
<br>
